ğŸ”¹ What kubectl drain Does

kubectl drain <node> = "I want to safely empty this node of pods so I can take it offline."

The command: kubectl drain <node-name>

is used when you want to safely remove all workloads (pods) from a node so that you can:

Do maintenance (upgrade kernel, patch OS, reboot)

Decommission the node

Upgrade Kubernetes itself 

-----------------------------
kubectl cordon <node> â†’ Marks node unschedulable (no new pods), but does not evict running pods.

kubectl uncordon <node> â†’ Marks node schedulable again, so new pods can run there.

kubectl delete node <node> â†’ Removes node object entirely from cluster (after draining).
